The effect of pH on the performance of the NIP and the MIP was explored and the results are shown in Fig. 5
                        . The enhanced fluorescence intensity was found to be little bit higher at pH 8.0 than that at pH 7.0. However, the imprinted factor reached the maximum at pH 7.0. Therefore, pH 7.0 was selected as the optimal pH value for subsequent experiments. The effect of temperature on the performance of NIP and MIP was also studied (Fig. 6
                        ). The fluorescence intensities showed a declining trend with increase in temperature from 25 to 60 °C. Since the fluorescence intensity was relatively strong at room temperature, 25 °C was chosen as the optimal temperature. Moreover, all operations at room temperature could be performed conveniently without sacrificing high detection sensitivity.
